name "subsec:ModelDynamics"

\end_inset

Model Specification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the properties of the utility function discussed so far, we now discuss
 how the observed variables which the consumer evaluates to exercise her
 choice of quality that is turn measured as the distance from cost of basic
 needs.
 These observed variables are the i) needs of the consumer ii) her income
 and iii) the assets she owns.
 To measure the quality chosen by the consumer, we observe the consumption
 within certain categories (which for in the current chapter are food, energy,
 transport and household).
 These variables are then assimilated in the Euler equations of the intertempora
l substitution problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The additive form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon(A,\rho,\nu)$
\end_inset

 means that there is a substitution between quality and assets.
 A consumer could achieve the same utility - inclusive of status - as that
 of a consumer with with higher education or higher asset ownership by raising
 her high-quality consumption.
 Similarly, the asset-owners need not purchase quality to stay ahead of
 others.
 Empirically, however, we note that high quality in non-durable often is
 constrained by asset ownership.
 Those who own a refrigerator spend less on kerosene for their energy needs
 compared to those who don't own a refrigerator.
 If we measure quality as the distance from cost of needs, there is a sunken
 cost the refrigerator owner incurs due to her asset ownership.
 If we wish to view quality after having conditioned for such costs in order
 to avoid double-counting the advantage the asset owner has, we ought to
 separate the quality demanded by the consumer from that which is incurred
 due to asset ownership.
 To ask whether the refrigerator owners spend more on exotic fruits than
 those those who don't, we must separate the running costs of the refrigerator
 from the measurement of quality control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Two measures address this standardisation of demand - first is the classificati
on of quality in separable commodities e.g.
 food, energy so that we may compare demand for quality in food with that
 for quality in household goods or transport.
 The second is the introduction of a cost-function 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 - which accounts for the cost of maintaining assets or similar characteristics
 (such as education or social class) 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is possible that ownership of some assets generates some rental income.
 Although we haven't found the significance of such income in the consumption
 data, we would prefer to treat such income as an additional stream of income
 instead treating it as negative costs in the model.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This takes care of the peer-effects to some extent - giving more weight
 to quality consumed by non-asset owners than would be if we didn't include
 the cost of assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:NeedsProcess"

\end_inset

Needs of the consumer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have briefly discussed in the Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:nonstochproblem"

\end_inset

, our notion of quality is dependent on what we consider as needs rather
 than the characteristics of items (see Rosen
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RosenImplicitHedonic1974"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a summary of hedonic approaches).
 We define needs as the standard requirements not meeting which would lead
 to a definite harm (this is in accordance to the theory argued for by Doyal
 and Gough 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 To an argument that a family can survive on just starch, the counter-argument
 would be that a foreseeable damage to the health of the consumer incurred
 by not having other nutrients is definite - thus ruling out a starch diet
 fulfilling the set of dietary needs.
 However, such a theory of needs is a normative concern (rather than descriptive
) - as a consumer may not always want her needs.
 Such a model for needs cannot represent a situation where consumers forgo
 a certain need to compromise on their health or autonomy in favour of some
 other wants.
 This makes the task to ensure that the needs are indeed just a minimum
 necessary set for health and autonomy to the individual extremely important.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider the minimum requirements for commodities such as food, clothing,
 housing and employment and calculate the costs associated with them in
 the local context (at a district level in the Tanzanian data - for example).
 The cost of the basic requirements per head 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 thus calculated are then multiplied with the number of family members 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the cost of needs of the household (
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}\cdot\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

).
 Relying only on total costs associated with a commodity (i.e.
 without using the quantity consumed), this notion of quality cannot differentia
te between the consumption of a higher quantity and of a higher quality.
 Consider for example, a household with a single member having consuming
 the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 for a commodity priced 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 If the minimum requirement for basic needs is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi=p_{1}q_{0}$
\end_inset

, then our quality metric for the consumer is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p_{1}q_{1}}{p_{1}q_{0}}=\frac{q_{1}}{q_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 For the individual's household, consuming more quantity than the minimum
 may increase the measure of quality much the way it would if she had switched
 to a better quality.
 As the consumption surveys often don't record the quantity consumed for
 non-food commodities e.g.
 clothing, toiletries etc.
 (nor the associated brand information), there is no way for us to distinguish
 between over-consumption and high-quality consumption by relying solely
 on the total consumption on the good (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot q=\sum_{i}p_{i}q_{i}=x$
\end_inset

).
 However, as we do know whether the range of goods within a commodity are
 available in the region or not, it may be possible to draw conclusions
 about over-consumption and higher-quality consumption for a group of consumers
 - separated by region or other characteristics - who face different ranges
 of goods available within a commodity.
 This is particularly so when using pseudo-panel analyses for the data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whether we model the needs of the household as a unit that lives forever
 (dynasty) or as a household individual with a finite lifetime 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, the evolution of needs as the number of living family members at a certain
 period must be aligned with the population trends in the economy.
 In the particular context of a developing country, we find that the expected
 path of needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(t,T)$
\end_inset

 is influenced with a high population growth rate and prevalence of a joint-fami
ly structure.
 Based on the data observed in the sub-Saharan African countries, we consider
 the functional form 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(t,T)=\mathbbm{1}_{t<T}\mu te^{-\kappa t^{2}}$
\end_inset

 to map the age 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 of the household head to the expected value of number of members of the
 household at time time (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(t,T)$
\end_inset

).
 We assume that this trajectory of needs is known to the consumer and that
 she adjusts her consumption according to this trajectory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Income Process
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
The goal of using an income process in the model is to provide an exogenous
 way to differentiate increase in household incomes from the accumulation
 of assets.
 It is the substitution of the latter with consumption that is crucial to
 our interpretation of status consumption as a quality scale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike in PIH, we hope that accumulaton of long-term assets have an influence
 on the subsitution between savings and quality.
 This should be included in the intertemporal settings just alongside with
 permanent income - which too is a risk-adjusted income (only that it focuses
 on the monetary risk i.e.
 the volatility in income).
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We attach no uncertainty to the growth of income in the non-stochastic model.
 Thus the growth rate would remain the same forever and is known to the
 consumer.
 In the stochastic model, on the other hand, one could let the consumer
 maintain two uncertainties - the first being in how her annual income unfolds
 in her future years and the second before how she becomes part of a stable
 high-consumption club through means other than income growth.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Empirically, this means that while the exogenous income process may depend
 on education or occupation levels, the effect that long-term characteristics
 have on consumption are not necessarily through income but through constraints
 or the stability that the long-term characteristics and expectations may
 bring.
 As the effects of on consumption are modeled explicitly, it would suffice
 if the income process models an expectation of the monetary growth alone
 i.e.
 a reflection of the steady growth in the economy on to the consumer's budget.
 For the analysis of the Tanzanian data therefore, we have assumed an income
 process with a steady rate of growth 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 every year i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}=i_{0}k^{t}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the starting income, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 the time period and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 the rate of growth per period.
 Here, the past values of 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 do not influence the current and future values of (or influence them only
 through long-term characteristics characteristics such as education).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Change in asset ownership over time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wealth of a consumer is represented in the model with a combination
 of accumulated assets and long-term characteristics (education, occupation
 or social identity).
 The asset ownership is modeled with an asset account - whose value is reflected
 in the total cost of assets inclusive of cash assets that the consumer
 owns.
 The use of such an asset account implies that no distinction is made between
 the accumulation of cash reserved to purchase assets and the actual purchase
 of assets.
 Thus if a consumer sets her eyes on assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 (that have prices 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{A}<\Pi_{B}$
\end_inset

) and the value of her cash account at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}=\Pi_{A}$
\end_inset

, then the model does not distinguish between the case when she buys the
 asset 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (price 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{A}$
\end_inset

) and the case when she forgoes the purchase of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to save for the future purchase of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 ( prices 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{B}>\Pi_{A}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to view the asset account is to consider that all assets in
 the economy are managed by a large firm (owing its success to preferences
 being the same for everybody) that provides furniture, housing and all
 amenities at a flat upfront cost.
 Every asset and service - offered as a life-long subscription - can be
 purchased by giving an amount to this company.
 We also assume that at the of the lifetime of a consumer, her personal
 wealth would either be consumed or would be passed on to her progeny so
 that the asset account at the end of the lifetime becomes starting wealth
 of someone else in the economy.
 Consequently, while all individuals in the population are assumed to be
 the same as our representative consumer in terms of the preferences for
 needs over quality, they differ in the the starting amount of their asset
 accounts as well as the trends of their salaries, the trajectory of their
 needs and their long-term quality habits.
 If a consumer has a starting income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}$
\end_inset

 and a steady growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, she would after 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 years of working her salary is 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}k^{\tau}$
\end_inset

 and the total income she has earned is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{\tau}i_{j}=\frac{i_{0}k}{k-1}(k^{\tau}-1)$
\end_inset

.
 At a given time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, she could have purchased assets from a portion of her income and decided
 that she does not want more assets for the rest of her life.
 Alternatively, her life circumstances might have changed (she may need
 a bigger house or want a more expensive house) thus needing more assets
 urgently.
 The consumption in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 would therefore depend on the needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, asset account value 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In a probabilistic model, we would attach a consumer probability of these
 events occurring at different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 This is postponed until a stochastic model is considered.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the consumption of quality in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity, we also assume an environment of zero interest and one where
 no depreciation is associated with the assets (which are easy to introduce
 if considered necessary) is assumed.
 Also, due to the minimal presence of credit facilities in the developing
 countries, we assume a negligible credit in the market.
 This in turn implies that the consumer can only save to buy more of the
 only asset available in the market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:nonstochproblem"

\end_inset

Intertemporal substitution model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the variables needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

, owned assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

, income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 and observed consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 that are observed in the data, we now turn to a quality control in the
 Euler equations of the intertemporal setting that represents the consumer
 choice for quality.
 By definition of the needs, a consumer is meant to select a quality control
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 only after her needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

 and those imposed by the owned assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and her personal characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 are fulfilled (the lack of subscript in 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is due to the assumption that the personal characteristics don't change
 in the near-term analysis).
 Thus we view the quality control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 (in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) as a multiplier of the cost of needs - the higher its value the higher
 would be the distance from the basic needs consumption (and lower would
 be the future growth of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
One could also introduce some inertia for quality in the model by considering
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{w}$
\end_inset

 a long-term habit of the consumer that remains the same over the period
 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Other than the control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, the consumption depends both on needs and the long-term choices of the
 consumer (which are encapsulated by the asset 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 the consumer has accumulated in the past and the the personal characteristics
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 she possesses).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-durable costs imposed by the assets one possesses (e.g.
 fuel for cars, electricity for heating equipment, rent/maintenance-fees
 for housing etc.) imply either that avoiding the respective expenses is
 not an option for the consumer owning some assets or that some certain
 long-term choices or characteristics (e.g.
 not having a house or living in a region that doesn't have electricity
 available) would limit the choice to avail quality through non-durable
 consumption.
 For example, a homeowner is required to maintain her own house the way
 someone who doesn't own the house has to pay the rent.
 As some costs are incurred due to the assets that the consumer acquires,
 a distance from the basic needs (which are themselves imposed only by health
 and autonomy requirements) could be introduced as the consumer acquires
 more assets.
 Such 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

enhanced
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 needs of the consumer as she acquires assets necessitate a parameter in
 the model that is different from the quality control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 and separates how much the consumer choice is related to her long-term
 standing influenced by 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 from how much quality is demanded in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 This former constraint is provided with the cost-function 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 - which along with the quality control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 selected by the consumer contributes to the consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 thus adjusts the non-durable consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 with the costs incurred due to asset ownership (e.g.
 of maintenance fees or rent in the housing example).
 The Euler equations for this model are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\eta_{t}=\eta(t,T)\nonumber \\
A_{t+1}=A_{t}+(i_{t+1}-c_{t+1})\nonumber \\
i_{t+1}=ki_{t}\nonumber \\
c_{t+1}=(1+\nu_{t+1})\Psi_{t}\eta_{t}+p(A_{t},\rho)\label{eq:nonstoch}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

 represents the consumer need unit at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 the cost of needs per unit,
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the value of asset account in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 (comprising of cash reserved for assets as well as the total value of assets
 owned), 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 are the static household characteristics (educational level, religious
 or social identity etc.), 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the income obtained in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 the consumption in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The cost 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 represents the minimal per-head cost that a household has to maintain given
 her personal characteristics and owned assets.
 For example, the costs of housing that contribute to 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 may consist of the mortgage fee or maintenance fees when someone owns a
 house but a monthly rent when the consumer does not own a house.
 The effect of supply-related asymmetries in the data e.g.
 lack of availability of certain goods in a certain region etc.
 can also be accommodated with the function 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

.
 While 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 can be estimated from the data (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:EmpiricalAnalysis"

\end_inset

 ), we demonstrate a particular solution of the equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nonstoch"

\end_inset

 by assuming that the costs associated with the owned assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 or of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $mA_{t}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 where the characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 are (momentarily) considered a part of assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
One may add a function for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $b(\rho)$
\end_inset

 or consider the more realistic scenario where 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A,\rho)$
\end_inset

 is a filter function that assigns levels of consumption (rather than exact
 contributions to 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

) based on 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the observed variables 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t},A_{t},\rho,i_{t},\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

, the consumer optimises the non-stochastic sum 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\sum_{i=1}^{T}\upsilon(\nu_{i},A_{i},\rho_{i})$
\end_inset

 over her life-time of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 years.
 The consumer chooses 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t+1}\ge0$
\end_inset

 in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to consume the quality she desires.
 The minimum cost for maintaining the needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

 in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are meant to be chosen by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=0$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming a log-linear form of the utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon$
\end_inset

, the consumer optimises 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}(\alpha\nu_{i}+\beta\cdot ln\ A_{i}+(1-\alpha-\beta)\cdot ln\ \rho_{i})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 are constants.
 Notice that since additivity discourages substitution, the low substitution
 between 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 makes the combined utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\upsilon(\nu_{i},A_{i},\rho_{i})$
\end_inset

 plausible 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonEconConsumer"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the dynamic optimisation problem of maximising 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{T}\upsilon(c_{i},A_{i},\eta_{i})$
\end_inset

, we also impose the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}\ge c_{t}$
\end_inset

 to ensure that the consumer does not exercise the choice to sell assets
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 in order to consume.
 In the equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nonstochll"

\end_inset

, the value 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 represents the consumption in the year 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

 and thus the consumption in the first year (
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

) is part of the initial condition - as is the value 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 .
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t},c_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

, the consumer must choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 so that the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha log(A_{t+1})+\beta log(\nu_{t+1})+(1-\alpha-\beta)log(\rho_{t+1})$
\end_inset

 is maximised.
 Since the consumer does not exercise any choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

, we can focus on 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta log(c_{t+1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha log(A_{t+1})$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 that maximises 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon(c_{t+1},A_{t+1},\rho)$
\end_inset

 would satisfy the first-order condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\upsilon_{t+1}}{\partial\nu_{t+1}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The optimal solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 can thus be solved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\because\frac{\partial\upsilon_{t+1}}{\partial\nu_{t+1}}=\frac{\alpha}{A_{t+1}}\frac{\partial A_{t+1}}{\partial\nu_{t+1}}+\frac{\beta}{\nu_{t+1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial A_{t+1}}{\partial\nu_{t+1}}=-\eta_{t}\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\therefore$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\beta}{\nu_{t+1}}=\frac{\alpha\eta_{t}\Psi_{t}}{A_{t+1}}$
\end_inset

 .
 Thus, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\eta_{t}\Psi_{t}\nu_{t+1} & =\frac{\beta}{\alpha}A_{t+1}\label{eq:vtplusoptim}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nonstoch"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:vtplusoptim"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t+1}=\Psi_{t}\eta_{t}+\frac{\beta}{\alpha}A_{t+1}+p(A_{t},\rho)=\Psi_{t}\eta_{t}+\frac{\beta}{\alpha}(A_{t}+ki_{t}-c_{t+1})+p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 .
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c_{t+1} & =\frac{\alpha}{(\alpha+\beta)}\Psi_{t}\eta_{t}+\frac{\beta}{(\alpha+\beta)}A_{t}+\frac{\beta k}{(\alpha+\beta)}i_{t}+\frac{\beta}{(\alpha+\beta)}p(A_{t},\rho)\label{eq:nonstochsol}
\end{align}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above equation can be used to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\beta}{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 To consider the solution for a particular form of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 assume the needs function discussed in the Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:NeedsProcess"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A,t)=mA_{t}^{a}$
\end_inset

 so that Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nonstoch"

\end_inset

 can be reformulated as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
